Abstract
Health issues are something that almost everyone struggles with. By identifying risk factors and causes for different health issues (mental or physical), our team hopes to generate insights that can be used to better address them. We aim to do this by first identifying who is most at risk for suicide and if mental health resources/quality of life impacts suicide rates. Next, we want study how the working environment impacts mental health. Lastly, we want to address what day-to-day factors impact physical health. Researching these questions, we found that despite there being no strong relationship between suicide and availability of mental health resources, men and the elderly are generally at higher risk for suicide. Interventions targeting these demographics and ensuring funding for resources that have been already established is something that mental health professionals and lawmakers should prioritize. We also found that implementation of a strong mental health benefit system could benefit health in the workplace. Lastly, improving family planning and general healthcare accessibility in addition to increasing immunization rates could improve the physical health of a population.

1 Background / Motivation

Nearly everyone struggles with or knows someone that struggles with some form of a health issue (mental or physical). We want to look into the risk factors and associations for various health problems. Our goal is to gain some insight into what is relevant/related to the health issues each of us are exploring and identifying who is most at risk. Doing so can allow us to develop ideas or solutions to address many of these health issues that people face today. The topic of mental health is especially important as it is one of the top ten health issues plaguing people today [1], yet a stigma still exists around this topic in many parts of the world. Mental health conditions arenât always obvious and certain conditions can be hard to diagnose, making it essential to understand who is most at risk and if there are any potential associations for mental health problems with any factors.

We believe that this topic of health is one that is applicable to nearly anyone. We also believe that the insights generated can be of great use and benefit to society.

2 Problem statement

Davis: I aim to investigate trends relating to one of the most dire consequences of poor mental health: suicide. Specifically, I aim to investigate who is most risk for suicide utilzing a global database of suicide rates and mental health resources. I aim to find (on a global scale) if any demographics exhibit a heightened vulnerability to suicide and if an answer can be found in the availability of mental health resources.

Kaitlin: I am looking at a dataset related to mental health and specifically the employees in tech companies. I aim to investigate the relationship between the external factors that a company can provide and how they can be influencing a personâs mental health and their working performance

Andy: Iâm looking into what physical factors (and general factors) in day-to-day life are most coinciding with physical illnesses and poor health in India. I want to find the socio-economic and health factors (if any) that can be used to predict increased vulnerability to health issues such as chronic illness and death.

3 Data sources

The data used by Davis Johnson is from one open-source link containing four different files relating to data on suicide rates and mental health resources. One dataset includes the age-standardized suicide rates for both males and females of over 150 countries, while another includes the crude suicide rates for different age groups of each country for both males and females. The other two datasets include information on the availablility of various mental health resources per 100,000 people of each country. One of these datasets includes information on human resources such as the number of psychologists per 100,000 people of each country, and the other includes information on mental health facilities such as the number of mental hospitals per 100,000 people of each country. A small issue with these two datasets is that it includes just a little over 100 countries, compared to over 150 in the previous two datasets discussed. Additionally, as the next section shows, there are several missing values for some of these variables, which can impact the validity of some of my analyses. I decided to leave these missing values as null and thus excluding them from my analyses.

data: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/twinkle0705/mental-health-and-suicide-rates

The data used by Kaitlin Sun is from a mental status survey for tech company employees. It provides information about the objective and subjective working environment in relation to mental health suport and mental history of indiviudals of the employees. Questions in the dataset include whether mental illness has interfered with oneâs work(mental history), whether the company offers space for mental illness converstaions(objective accommodation), and whether the employee feel comfortable discussing mental status with a coworker or supervisor (subjective working environment).

data: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/osmi/mental-health-in-tech-survey?resource=download

The data used by Andy Wen is from an annual health survey conducted by Indiaâs government in nine states, accounting for about 48 percent of the total population. This dataset has responses from thousands of respondants covering 26 key indicator topics including information about chronic illnesses, childhood diseases, and overall death rates within India. This data will allow our team to see where relationships exist between these physical health issues and everyday statistics such as household characteristics, effective literacy rate, and marraige. Doing this, we can see what (if any) datapoints are most related to the having these health issues which we can later dive deeper into.

data: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rajanand/key-indicators-of-annual-health-survey

4 Stakeholders

The result can be helpful for the average person, health experts and researchers, and lawmakers.

It will be helpful for providing insights on the importance of mental/physical care for any individual in different environments. It will make a strong argument for individuals to focus on self-care. Likewise, companies and professional environments to will be more likely to focus on offering support to their workers. Lawmakers will also be equipped with the relevant information in order to establish appropriate funding for targeted interventions that can help people with vulnerabilities. It will also give ideas on different programs that can be created to improve the health and well being of those at risk.

With medical technology becoming more and more advanced, it will be helpful for researchers to be equipped with the necessary information to conduct targeted investigations into those who exhibit the most risk factors for various health problems.

6.1 Question 1: Who is most at risk for suicide? Is the availability of mental health resources associated with suicide risk across the globe?

By Davis Johnson

In this question, I attempted to analyze general suicide trends across the world through the 21st century up to 2016. The âAge-standardized suicide ratesâ datasets was used for the purposes of this analysis as it is the only dataset I used that had suicide rates for multiple years. Additionally, having the suicide rates be provided as age-standardized is useful in order to compare suicide rates across country and sex because the age composition of each country can greatly differ in both size and distribution. Additionally, this helps protect against these different age distributions from influencing the overall suicide rate of the country.

Because there are so many columns and information, I decided to put them into categories based on my question and hypothesis the first category is the dependent variable, which is a personâs mental health. To do so, I combined the treatment, family history, and work_interfere column: if a person has had treatment, we expect that s/he has experience a certain degree of mental illness, which is a score of 3; and depending on how often the symptom affect oneâs work, there are three four levels of severity. If a person has family history of mental illness, then we would expect that some of the mental health status is unrelated to the working environment, thus 2 points is subtracted. All information combined is the dependent variable: the mental illness score.

Code 
#dependent variable: mental illness score the lower the better
mental_survey['work_interfere'] = mental_survey['work_interfere'].replace(np.nan, 'Rarely' )
mental_survey['score'] = 0
for index, row in mental_survey.iterrows():
    if row['treatment'] == 'Yes':
        mental_survey['score'][index] += 3
    if row['work_interfere'] == 'Often':
        mental_survey['score'][index] += 3
    if row['work_interfere'] == 'Sometimes':
        mental_survey['score'][index] += 2
    if row['work_interfere'] == 'Rarely':
        mental_survey['score'][index] += 1
    if row['family_history'] == 'Yes':
        mental_survey['score'][index] -= 2
    count += 1

The second category is the objective company benefits, which are the fact-based information that all people from the same company should give the same answer. It includes information such as if the company offer care option for mental health, if there are wellness program and help provided, if it is possible/ easy to take a mental leave etc. Any yes gives 2 points to the score and no gives -2, and maybe is a 0.

Code 
#independent variable: company benefit [objective] the higher the better

Total households and population are also moderately correlated with acute illness rates (>= 0.5) which can be a result of largely populated areas having more people that interact and can spread illnesses.

7 Conclusions

On a global scale, men and the elderly are at heightened risk for suicide, and this canât necessarily be explained by the availability of various mental health resources or lack thereof. Some potential explanations are that traditional views surrounding masculinity encourage men not to be communicative or open about their mental health problems [2] and while women attempt suicide more than men, men are more likely to employ deadlier methods such as firearms [3]. Some potential explanations for higher suicide rates among the elderly are grief over lost loved ones, loss of self-sufficiency, chronic illness/pain, as well as cognitive impairment [4]. These explanation shine a light on the fact that ways to effectively target a specific medical issue might not always come via direct intervention, but rather targeting improvements in other areas that can serve as risk factors for the main problem. For example, establishing effective grief counseling for the elderly might have a positive impact on their suicide rates or establishing stricter gun laws might force men to seek less-deadly methods for attempting suicide.

In India, rural areas are more prone to poor physical health in the form of higher crude death rates and higher acute illness rates. Some potential explanations, as discussed above, include lower immunization rates among children as well as a lack of availability in family planning. Both of these factors were shown to have strong correlations with either crude death rates, chronic illness rates, and/or acute illness rates. We also see that rural areas have lower immunization rates and lower family planning usage which helps to explain this disparity. Immunization directly helps prevent diseases and illnesses such as diarrhea which can be incredibly deadly, especially for children which explains why death rates may be higher in certain areas like rural regions. Meanwhile family planning is a critical form of healthcare that can impact the livelihood of an entire family and thus their health. A lack of accessibility in healthcare such as family planning can be a reason why certain areas have poorer health. Overall, these explanations present an opportunity to improve the physical livelihoods of many, especially in India. Pushing for greater healthcare accessibility in rural regions throughout the country can help increase immunization rates and family planning usage which are both related to poor physical health. In addition, we see that women are disproportionately impacted by acute illnesses and chronic illnesses. Increasing outreach towards women and others in rural areas can be a way to go about improving physical health in India. Lastly, we saw that men have higher crude death rates which can be partially explained by much of the mental health analysis done above.

In terms of mental health, it is clear that company benefits has a impact on their employeeâs mental status and thus their potential work performance. There is clearly a gap between different countries, which I think is an important notice and that it will be improtant to close the gap. Moreover, although personal opinions have little to do with the mental score, the actual benefit is improtant. By noticing the difference among demographic and different companies, the dataset also shows that different companies may have different requests and emphasis on the mental health service they would want to provide to the employees.

There are always some external predictors that are avoidable or have the potential of being amended to improve the results such as mental illness, suicide, or illness. It can be information for individuals to take care of themselves and insights for lawmakers and researchers to look into to make social changes that benefit all people.

8 Recommendations to stakeholder(s)

On a broad scale, suicide interventions should be developed that place special emphasis on messaging that targets men and the elderly. Additionally, the lack of correlation between the quantity mental health resources and suicide rates suggest that the effectiveness of our facilities, mental health workers, and developed interventions is based on their preparedness and ability to provide effective care rather than their quantity. Instead of providing funding for more mental health resources on a global scale, organizations should advocate for ensuring that the existing structures in place have enough resources to provide quality care and implement effective anti-suicide prevention techniques. Additionally, more research emphasis should be placed on the systemic causes of males and the elderly generally having higher suicide rates and developing interventions that effectively target these demographics.

However, some of limitations of the above suicide analyses should be addressed. While the countries are grouped by continent, it is entirely possible that grouping the countries by other indicators is more appopriate to diagnose trends (such as first world, second world, and third world). Because of the broad nature of this analysis, the variability between countries from the same continent is not accounted for. More research needs to be done in order to examine the cultural and economic differences in different countries and how they play a role in suicide. Stakeholders should delve deeper into these factors to develop nuanced interventions that can be tailored for specific cultures/regions/and demographics.

Increasing immunization rates for children should be a top priority for any government (especially Indiaâs government) looking to improve physical health among the population. There should be an additional emphasis towards targeting rural regions where immunization rates and overall healthcare availability may be lacking. This can be done by opening more clinics in areas that are far away from any currently available option. Increasing accessibility also means making it price accessible which may not be the case in rural areas where the average income may be lower than urban areas. Also, increasing awareness of ORS and Zinc through advertisement or school can be a great way to decrease crude death rates since those are treatments for diarrhea. One limitation is that this analysis uses data that is nearly a decade old and specific to 9 states that make up a minority of Indiaâs population. Thus, performing this same analysis on a more updated and wide spanning survey can be a way to get the best possible results. Stakeholders that hope to use these solutions outside of India also need to be aware of how different the demographic/socio-economic factors may look in their own areas compared to India. Indiaâs rural population percentage is incredibly high compared to its urban population which can explain some of the results seen. Stakeholders will need to tailor their actions to the area they hope to apply these solutions.

Similarly, increasing accessibility of family planning practices as well as general healthcare can be a great way for governments to improve physical health as well. Opening clinics in remote areas and improving access can cut down acute illness rates, especially in rural regions. Having the option of using family planning practices impacts everything from health to income within the family and making sure that it is available is a great step towards improving physical and potentially mental health. This recommendation faces the same issues as the one above. It is based on an outdated data source and is only applicable to India.

Making healthcare more accessible for women can also help with cutting down on chronic/acute illness rates since we see that women have higher rates of chronic/acute illnesses compared to men. This can be done through opening more clinics/hospitals in remote areas as well as advertising/performing outreach about womenâs healthcare. This recommendation also faces the same issues that the above recommendations face. It is based on a decade old data source and is really only applicable to India. A stakeholder would have to customize these solutions based on the demographics and socio-economic realities in their countries/areas of interest.

For mental health, it is important to standardize some of the benefits and programs working environment should provide to people and narrow the gaps between the mental health service in different countries. Also, acknowledging the gender, age, and race difference and how all demographic difference play in the role of how comfortable people feel in the working environment and make explicit effort to make an inclusive environment that people comfortable opening up to someone when they need the help.

From the perspective of the company, it is true that mental disorder and illness can be interruptive to peopleâs working environment. Thus It will beneficial for the company as well if the companies invest in a strong mental health benefit system.
